The paper discusses a new operator for in-database analytics tasks that deals with managing models with millions or billions of parameters that do not fit in memory. This suggests that the paper is likely to belong to the database (cs.DB) and machine learning (cs.LG) sub-categories. Additionally, the paper proposes a solution to the problem of scheduling access to a dense relation based on sparse non-contiguous entries in sparse arrays, which involves optimization and algorithmic design. This suggests that the paper may also belong to the data structures (cs.DS), information retrieval (cs.IR), and artificial intelligence (cs.AI) sub-categories.
